				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "## 8. Key Considerations for Pharo/Smalltalk Client\n\n1. **Multipart form upload** -- The script upload endpoint requires `multipart/form-data`. `ZnClient` supports this via `ZnMultiPartFormDataEntity`. Two parts needed: `metadata` (JSON string as `application/json`) and the script file (JavaScript with `application/javascript+module` content type for ES modules).\n\n2. **workers.dev gives instant URLs** -- No DNS configuration needed. Upload a script and it is immediately accessible at `https://{name}.{subdomain}.workers.dev`. This is the simplest path for webhook hosting.\n\n3. **KV vs D1 for storage** -- KV is simpler (key-value, eventually consistent, good for event logs with timestamp-prefixed keys). D1 is a full SQLite database (good for structured queries, filtering, relational data). For webhook event capture, KV with TTL may be sufficient.\n\n4. **No Wrangler needed** -- Every operation (create script, bind KV, set routes, enable subdomain) is available via REST API. The metadata JSON in the multipart upload fully replaces `wrangler.toml`.\n\n5. **Script names are URL-safe identifiers** -- They appear in the workers.dev URL and route configuration. Use lowercase alphanumeric with hyphens.\n\n6. **Response envelope** -- All Cloudflare API responses follow `{ success, errors, messages, result }`. Always check `success` first, then inspect `errors` array for details. Error objects include `code`, `message`, and `documentation_url`.\n\n7. **Request body can only be read once** -- In the Worker script, `request.text()` / `request.json()` consumes the body. Use `request.clone()` if you need to read it multiple times (e.g., for logging and forwarding)."
			}
